In the complex network of genes, they work together to carry out various functions, influencing different biological processes related to diseases [@pmid:19104045; @doi:10.1038/ng.3259]. Variations in these genes can lead to changes in their functional roles at a higher level, affecting the disease-relevant biological processes [@doi:10.1038/s41467-018-06022-6]. Understanding how these genes influence complex traits requires examining gene expression regulation across different cell types, which in turn should lead to improved treatments [@doi:10.1038/ng.3314; @doi:10.1371/journal.pgen.1008489].

Previous studies have described various regulatory DNA elements, including genetic effects on gene expression across different tissues [@doi:10.1126/science.aaz1776; @pmid:31036433; @doi:10.1038/nature14248]. Integrating functional genomics data and GWAS data has improved the identification of transcriptional mechanisms that, when dysregulated, commonly result in tissue- and cell lineage-specific pathology [@pmid:20624743; @pmid:14707169; @doi:10.1038/s41588-018-0081-4; @doi:10.1016/j.ajhg.2018.04.002; @pmid:33931583]. However, there is still a knowledge gap regarding how these mechanisms contribute to disease etiology and drug mechanisms, which this manuscript seeks to address by highlighting the importance of gene co-expression in understanding complex traits and identifying therapeutic targets for drug repurposing and clustering [@doi:10.1038/s41586-020-2559-3; @pmid:33931583].<|end_of_turn|>

In the context of genes working together in specific networks, variations in these genes can change their functional role and impact disease-relevant biological processes. Understanding how genes influence complex traits requires examining gene expression regulation across different cell types, which should lead to improved treatments. Previous studies have described various regulatory DNA elements, including genetic effects on gene expression across different tissues. Integrating functional genomics data with GWAS data has helped identify transcriptional mechanisms that, when dysregulated, often result in tissue- and cell lineage-specific pathology. Our study aims to build upon this knowledge by investigating the relationship between gene co-expression patterns, genetic associations, and their implications for disease etiology and drug mechanisms, addressing a significant gap in our understanding of these complex processes.

In this context, determining how genes influence complex traits requires mechanistically understanding gene expression regulation across different cell types, which should lead to improved treatments. Previous studies have described various regulatory DNA elements, including genetic effects on gene expression across different tissues. Integrating functional genomics data with GWAS data has helped identify transcriptional mechanisms that, when dysregulated, often result in tissue- and cell lineage-specific pathology. Our study aims to build upon this knowledge by investigating the relationship between gene co-expression patterns, genetic associations, and their implications for disease etiology and drug mechanisms, addressing a significant gap in our understanding of these complex processes.

Our research seeks to contribute to the existing body of knowledge by examining how genetic studies, functional genomics, gene co-expression, therapeutic targets, and drug repurposing can shed light on disease etiology and drug mechanisms. By clustering complex traits through gene expression patterns, we hope to better understand the underlying biological processes that contribute to various diseases and inform the development of targeted treatments.

In summary, our study aims to enhance our understanding of genetic associations by investigating their relationship with gene expression patterns. We believe that this approach will provide valuable insights into disease etiology and drug mechanisms, ultimately contributing to the development of more effective therapies for a range of conditions.<|end_of_turn|>

In the complex web of gene interactions, genes work together in specific networks to carry out various functions [@pmid:19104045; @doi:10.1038/ng.3259]. Variations in these genes can change their functional role and, at a higher level, affect disease-relevant biological processes [@doi:10.1038/s41467-018-06022-6]. Understanding how genes influence complex traits requires examining gene expression regulation across different cell types [@doi:10.1126/science.aaz1776; @doi:10.1038/s41586-020-2559-3; @doi:10.1038/s41576-019-0200-9], which in turn should lead to improved treatments [@doi:10.1038/ng.3314; @doi:10.1371/journal.pgen.1008489].

Previous studies have identified different regulatory DNA elements, such as genetic effects on gene expression across various tissues [@doi:10.1126/science.aaz1776; @pmid:31036433], including transcriptional mechanisms that, when dysregulated, commonly result in tissue- and cell lineage-specific pathology [@pmid:20624743; @pmid:14707169; @doi:10.1073/pnas.0810772105]. Integrating functional genomics data and GWAS data has improved the identification of these mechanisms, shedding light on disease etiology and potential drug targets [@pmid:33931583; @doi:10.1038/s41588-018-0081-4; @doi:10.1016/j.ajhg.2018.04.002]. However, a significant knowledge gap remains in understanding the connections between gene co-expression, functional genomics, and their implications for therapeutic targets and drug repurposing strategies [@pmid:31036433; @doi:10.1038/s41586-020-2559-3]. This manuscript aims to address these gaps by exploring gene expression patterns, their connections with genetic associations, and the potential implications for disease etiology and drug mechanisms, ultimately contributing to the development of novel therapeutic targets and strategies for drug repurposing.<|end_of_turn|>

Transcription-wide association studies (TWAS) have emerged as an effective approach, integrating expression quantitative trait loci (eQTLs) data to provide a mechanistic interpretation for genome-wide association study (GWAS) findings [@doi:10.1038/nbt.3838; @doi:10.1038/s41467-018-03751-6; @doi:10.1126/science.aaz1776; @doi:10.1186/s13040-020-00216-9]. column1: Here we propose PhenoPLIER, an omnigenic approach that provides a gene module perspective to genetic studies. The flexibility of our method allows integrating different data modalities into the same representation for a joint analysis. We show that this module perspective can infer how groups of functionally-related genes influence complex traits, detect shared and distinct transcriptomic properties among traits, and predict how pharmacological perturbations affect genes' activity to exert their effects. PhenoPLIER maps gene-trait associations and drug-induced transcriptional responses into a common latent representation. For this, we integrate thousands of gene-trait associations (using TWAS from PhenomeXcan [@doi:10.1126/sciadv.aba2083]) and transcriptional profiles of drugs (from LINCS L1000 [@doi:10.1016/j.cell.2017.10.049]) into a low-dimensional space learned from public gene expression data on tens of thousands of RNA-seq samples (recount2 [@doi:10.1016/j.cels.2019.04.003; @doi:10.1038/nbt.3838]). We use a latent representation defined by a matrix factorization approach [@doi:10.1038/s41592-019-0456-1; @doi:10.1016/j.cels.2019.04.003] that extracts gene modules with certain sparsity constraints and preferences for those that align with prior knowledge (pathways). When mapping gene-trait associations to this reduced expression space, we observe that diseases are significantly associated with gene modules expressed in relevant cell types: such as hypothyroidism with T cells, corneal endothelial cells with keratometry measurements, hematological assays on specific blood cell types, plasma lipids with adipose tissue, and neuropsychiatric disorders with different brain cell types. Moreover, since PhenoPLIER can use models derived from large and heterogeneous RNA-seq datasets, we can also identify modules associated with cell types under specific stimuli or disease states. We observe that significant module-trait associations in PhenomeXcan (our discovery cohort) replicated in the Electronic Medical Records and Genomics (eMERGE) network phase III [@doi:10.1038/gim.2013.72; @doi:10.1101/2021.10.21.21265225] (our replication cohort). Furthermore, we perform a CRISPR screen to analyze lipid regulation in HepG2 cells. We observe more robust trait associations with modules than with individual genes, even when single genes known to be involved in lipid metabolism did not reach genome-wide significance. Compared to a single-gene approach, our module-based method also better predicts FDA-approved drug-disease links by capturing tissue-specific pathophysiological mechanisms linked with the mechanism of action of drugs (e.g., niacin with cardiovascular traits via a known immune mechanism). This improved drug-disease prediction suggests that modules may provide a better means to examine drug-disease relationships than individual genes. Finally, exploring the phenotype-module space reveals stable trait clusters associated with relevant tissues, including a complex branch involving lipids with cardiovascular, autoimmune, and neuropsychiatric disorders. In summary, instead of considering single genes associated with different complex traits, PhenoPLIER incorporates groups of genes that act together to carry out different functions in specific cell types. This approach improves robustness in detecting and interpreting genetic associations, and here we show how it can prioritize alternative and potentially more promising candidate targets even when known single gene associations are not detected. The approach represents a conceptual shift in the interpretation of genetic studies. It has the potential to extract mechanistic insight from statistical associations to enhance the understanding of complex diseases and their therapeutic modalities.

Here, we propose PhenoPLIER, an omnigenic approach that offers a gene module perspective for genetic studies. The flexibility of our method allows seamless integration of various data modalities into a single representation for comprehensive analysis. We demonstrate that the module perspective can reveal how groups of functionally-related genes influence complex traits, detect shared and distinct transcriptomic properties among traits, and predict pharmacological perturbations' effects on gene activity to exert their impact. PhenoPLIER converts gene-trait associations and drug-induced transcriptional responses into a common latent representation. For this purpose, we integrate thousands of gene-trait associations (from TWAS in PhenomeXcan [@doi:10.1126/sciadv.aba2083]) and transcriptional profiles of drugs (from LINCS L1000 [@doi:10.1016/j.cell.2017.10.049]) into a low-dimensional space derived from public gene expression data on tens of thousands of RNA-seq samples (recount2 [@doi:10.1016/j.cels.2019.04.003; @doi:10.1038/nbt.3838]). We employ a matrix factorization approach [@doi:10.1038/s41592-019-0456-1; @doi:10.1016/j.cels.2019.04.003] to define a latent representation with sparsity constraints and preferences for gene modules that align with prior knowledge (pathways). When mapping gene-trait associations onto this reduced expression space, we find significant associations between diseases and gene modules expressed in relevant cell types, such as hypothyroidism with T cells, corneal endothelial cells with keratometry measurements, hematological assays on specific blood cell types, plasma lipids with adipose tissue, and neuropsychiatric disorders with different brain cell types. Since PhenoPLIER can utilize models derived from large and heterogeneous RNA-seq datasets, we can also identify modules linked to cell types under specific stimuli or disease states. We observe that significant module-trait associations in PhenomeXcan (our discovery cohort) replicate in the Electronic Medical Records and Genomics (eMERGE) network phase III [@doi:10.1038/gim.2013.72; @doi:10.1101/2021.10.21.21265225] (our replication cohort). Additionally, we perform a CRISPR screen to analyze lipid regulation in HepG2 cells and find more robust trait associations with modules than with individual genes, even when single genes known to be involved in lipid metabolism did not reach genome-wide significance. In comparison to the single-gene approach, our module-based method offers better predictions of FDA-approved drug-disease links by capturing tissue-specific pathophysiological mechanisms related to the drugs' mechanism of action (e.g., niacin with cardiovascular traits via a known immune mechanism). This improved drug-disease prediction suggests that modules may provide a superior means of examining drug-disease relationships compared to individual genes. Ultimately, exploring the phenotype-module space reveals stable trait clusters linked to relevant tissues, including a complex branch involving lipids with cardiovascular, autoimmune, and neuropsychiatric disorders. In summary, PhenoPLIER offers an alternative approach to traditional genetic studies by examining groups of functionally-related genes acting together in specific cell types rather than single genes associated with different complex traits. This method enhances the robustness of detecting and interpreting genetic associations, allowing for the identification of potential alternative and more promising candidate targets even when known single gene associations are not detected. PhenoPLIER represents a paradigm shift in the interpretation of genetic studies, with the potential to extract mechanistic insights from statistical associations to deepen our understanding of complex diseases and their therapeutic modalities.<|end_of_turn|>

Here, we propose PhenoPLIER, an innovative method for analyzing genetic studies that focuses on groups of functionally-related genes, known as gene modules, rather than individual genes. Our approach is flexible and can integrate various types of data for joint analysis. By examining these gene modules, we can infer how they influence complex traits, detect shared and distinct features among different traits, and predict the impact of pharmacological interventions on gene activity.

PhenoPLIER combines thousands of gene-trait associations from TWAS in PhenomeXcan [@doi:10.1126/sciadv.aba2083] with transcriptional profiles of drugs from the LINCS L1000 project [@doi:10.1016/j.cell.2017.10.049]. These data are transformed into a low-dimensional space using public gene expression data from tens of thousands of RNA-seq samples, such as recount2 [@doi:10.1016/j.cels.2019.04.003; @doi:10.1038/nbt.3838]. This process involves a matrix factorization approach [@doi:10.1038/s41592-019-0456-1; @doi:10.1016/j.cels.2019.04.003] that identifies gene modules with certain sparsity constraints and preferences for those that align with prior knowledge (pathways).

When mapping gene-trait associations to this reduced expression space, we find that diseases are significantly associated with gene modules expressed in relevant cell types, such as hypothyroidism with T cells, keratometry measurements with corneal endothelial cells, and neuropsychiatric disorders with different brain cell types. Additionally, since PhenoPLIER can use models derived from large and heterogeneous RNA-seq datasets, we can also identify modules associated with specific cell types under certain stimuli or disease states.

Our results show that significant module-trait associations in PhenomeXcan (our discovery cohort) replicate in the Electronic Medical Records and Genomics (eMERGE) network phase III [@doi:10.1038/gim.2013.72; @doi:10.1101/2021.10.21.21265225] (our replication cohort). We also perform a CRISPR screen to analyze lipid regulation in HepG2 cells and find that trait associations with modules are more robust than those with individual genes, even when single genes known to be involved in lipid metabolism did not reach genome-wide significance.

Compared to a single-gene approach, our module-based method better predicts FDA-approved drug-disease links by capturing tissue-specific pathophysiological mechanisms linked with the mechanism of action of drugs (e.g., niacin with cardiovascular traits via a known immune mechanism). This improved drug-disease prediction suggests that modules may provide a better means to examine drug-disease relationships than individual genes.

Finally, exploring the phenotype-module space reveals stable trait clusters associated with relevant tissues, including a complex branch involving lipids with cardiovascular, autoimmune, and neuropsychiatric disorders. In summary, PhenoPLIER offers an innovative approach to analyzing genetic studies by focusing on gene modules rather than single genes, which improves robustness in detecting and interpreting genetic associations. This method has the potential to extract mechanistic insights from statistical associations to enhance our understanding of complex diseases and their therapeutic modalities, representing a conceptual shift in the interpretation of genetic studies.<|end_of_turn|>

Exploring the phenotype-module space reveals stable trait clusters associated with relevant tissues, including a complex branch involving lipids with cardiovascular, autoimmune, and neuropsychiatric disorders. Here, we propose PhenoPLIER, an omnigenic approach that offers a gene module perspective for genetic studies. Our method's flexibility allows the integration of diverse data modalities into a unified representation for joint analysis. We demonstrate that this module perspective can reveal how groups of functionally-related genes influence complex traits, detect shared and distinct transcriptomic properties among traits, and predict how pharmacological perturbations affect gene activity to exert their effects. PhenoPLIER maps gene-trait associations and drug-induced transcriptional responses into a common latent representation. For this purpose, we integrate thousands of gene-trait associations (using TWAS from PhenomeXcan [@doi:10.1126/sciadv.aba2083]) and transcriptional profiles of drugs (from LINCS L1000 [@doi:10.1016/j.cell.2017.10.049]) into a low-dimensional space derived from public gene expression data on tens of thousands of RNA-seq samples (recount2 [@doi:10.1016/j.cels.2019.04.003; @doi:10.1038/nbt.3838]). We employ a matrix factorization approach [@doi:10.1038/s41592-019-0456-1; @doi:10.1016/j.cels.2019.04.003] to define a latent representation with certain sparsity constraints and preferences for gene modules that align with prior knowledge (pathways). When mapping gene-trait associations to this reduced expression space, we observe significant associations between diseases and gene modules expressed in relevant cell types, such as hypothyroidism with T cells, corneal endothelial cells with keratometry measurements, hematological assays on specific blood cell types, plasma lipids with adipose tissue, and neuropsychiatric disorders with different brain cell types. Additionally, since PhenoPLIER can utilize models derived from large and heterogeneous RNA-seq datasets, we can identify modules associated with cell types under specific stimuli or disease states. Module-trait associations in PhenomeXcan (our discovery cohort) are replicated in the Electronic Medical Records and Genomics (eMERGE) network phase III [@doi:10.1038/gim.2013.72; @doi:10.1101/2021.10.21.21265225] (our replication cohort). Furthermore, we perform a CRISPR screen to analyze lipid regulation in HepG2 cells and observe more robust trait associations with modules than with individual genes, even when single genes known to be involved in lipid metabolism did not reach genome-wide significance. Compared to a single-gene approach, our module-based method provides better predictions of FDA-approved drug-disease links by capturing tissue-specific pathophysiological mechanisms linked with the mechanism of action of drugs (e.g., niacin with cardiovascular traits via a known immune mechanism). This improved drug-disease prediction suggests that modules may offer a superior means to examine drug-disease relationships compared to individual genes. Lastly, exploring the phenotype-module space reveals stable trait clusters associated with relevant tissues, including a complex branch involving lipids with cardiovascular, autoimmune, and neuropsychiatric disorders. In summary, PhenoPLIER shifts the focus from single genes associated with different complex traits to groups of functionally-related genes that act together in specific cell types. This approach enhances the robustness in detecting and interpreting genetic associations, and we demonstrate its potential to prioritize alternative and potentially more promising candidate targets even when known single gene associations are not detected. PhenoPLIER has the capacity to extract mechanistic insights from statistical associations, thereby improving our understanding of complex diseases and their therapeutic modalities.<|end_of_turn|>

This low-dimensional space is defined by a matrix factorization approach [@doi:10.1038/s41592-019-0456-1; @doi:10.1016/j.cels.2019.04.003] that extracts gene modules with certain sparsity constraints and preferences for those that align with prior knowledge (pathways).
